About two weeks after I received the vaccine (almost a week ago as of present) I began experiencing rapid muscle twitches near the injection site. I can send a video if necessary. Only muscle experiencing these symptoms is one on my left shoulder, where the injection occurred. Twitches a couple times a second for a couple minutes at a time. Frequency of these events per day has increased over the past week. Presents without pain, numbness, tingling, etc. No past history of chronic muscle twitches. I am capable of fine motor movements such as writing and maintaining full motion of my arm while it occurs. Consulted with a doctor (my employer) informally and they recommended I submit this form. Willing to answer any questions that might show up.

About 3 minutes after patient received immunization, he fainted and had a seizure. I monitored patient for about 45 minutes before I felt patient was stable and feeling well enough to leave. Patient left with his parents monitoring him.

18 2021-03-17 numbness Received first dose of Moderna vaccine today around 2:30 pm. Reports 2 minutes later, felt left side... Read more
Close
Received first dose of Moderna vaccine today around 2:30 pm. Reports 2 minutes later, felt left side of throat "swell" and was uncomfortable. Also felt mild chest discomfort. Symptoms resolved after about 3 minutes, so he finished his 15 minute observation time, and left the clinic. He returned approximately 15 mins later, and informed the ER MD here in the clinic that his throat swelling and tightness had returned and that he now had and some difficulty breathing. He was answering questions appropriately, appeared in no distress. At 1510 VS taken: BP 122/74, O2 sat 100%, P 73, RR 18. Skin color pink/normal. ER MD advised patient be taken to ER and he called report there. Patient was taken via WC right away to ER with MD, and RN and myself. Anaphylaxis kit brought. But not used. He was stable during transport. In ER he c/o more throat tightness, and it appeared that the left side of his neck was mildly swollen. He then c/o bilateral pedal numbness and also some difficulty breathing. Care was assumed by RN and report was given to her. He was able to call his parents prior and remained stable at the time we departed the ER. NP

After receiving vaccine, patient sat down for the 15 minute observation. He reports about 1-2 minutes after sitting down feeling flushed, lightheaded. Patient's color pale. EMS on site and took over triage of patient. BP 83/50, P 58-60. Patient reported eating a bar before coming. His blood sugar 111. Patient was given water to drink. BP increased to 100/62, color returning, still pale. He reports feeling better. He stood and sat in a w/c to take to the stretcher for additional observation. Patient ate a pack of peanut butter crackers, drank 1 16.9 oz bottle water, color pink, BP 121/76. Patient says he drove from DIFFRENT STATE to receive his vaccine and is alone. Patient reports feeling better. He was instructed to walk around, he did so without any complications, color remained pink. He says he feels better. After additional 15 minute observation, he was checked out. I instructed if the symptoms come back to pull over and call 911, he verbalized understanding.

This patient had some dizziness after the shot and was apprehensive in receiving it. He claimed he felt dizzy and in seconds had slumped off of his chair. He was unresponsive for a few seconds only about 5-10 seconds and we gave him an IM Benadryl as a precaution. He awoke complaining of a funny feeling in the mouth and tongue but had no rash or redness or swelling to indicate an allergic reaction. We decide to monitor closely for an escalation of symptoms but to have a EpiPen handy, and call an EMT unit. His blood pressure was low at first at around 107/68 then quickly come up in about 10 minutes to 130/80. With no other issues we believe he had a vasovagal syncope but wanted the ER to make sure we were correct. I called and checked on him after he was at the ER. and the nurse stated that he was doing very well and that they had seen this happen with the vaccine at other site locations.

Close
Pt had a vasovagal response to the vaccine. It happened right after administration. Patient started shaking and closed his eyes. Just a few seconds later he woke up and said something along the lines of, "Oh did I pass out?" I caught him in my arms before he could fall to the floor. The same response where he started aggressively shaking and eyes closed happened a few seconds later. His legs straightened out and his head was headed backward. Again I caught him and stabilized him. Afterward, my 2nd pharmacist stopped over and spoke with him. He seemed to be feeling better, but to ensure the same reaction wouldn't happen again, we had him wait 30 min instead of the standard 15. He sat in his chair and did not have any issues. We offered food but he was not interested. I spoke w/ him again this afternoon via phone and he said he was doing fine. Pt said he has had this type of rxn before w/ previous vaccines.

Developed "moderna arm" (raised inflammation with itching 1.5-2 inches long and 0.5-1 inches across) 7 days post vaccination from injection 1. Developed somewhat severe tension headache on day 1 post vaccination from injection 2 (all further events listed below are from injection 2). Headache responded to ibuprofen. On day 4 post vaccination, began experiencing minor and infrequent migraine-like headaches that lasted for a few seconds to a minute. Moderate pain and localized. Pain site changed but was generally on left side. Experienced 0-2 a day until day 12. On day 11 post vaccination, began experiencing full, moderate tension headache. In addition, had more frequent migraine-like headaches. Did not respond to 400mg ibuprofen or 10mg Claritin. On day 12 post vaccination, began experiencing photophobia. Mentioned to general practitioner out of an abundance of caution who recommended Excedrin. Took two Excedrin extra strength (total dosage: Acetomenaphin 500mg, Aspirin 500 mg, Caffeine 130 mg). Tension headache ended and most (but not all) migraine-like pain subsided. Some occasional pain ranging from 1-2 out of 10. On day 13 out of an abundance of caution following reports of other events I went to the ER. The doctor there examined for any cognitive symptoms (asked me to follow her finger with my eyes, squeeze fingers, checked ability to move extremities, etc) and concluded no risk of CVST. Determined that vaccine likely lowered my threshold for headaches and migraines (I have had very infrequent cluster headaches lasting for a few seconds in the past, never for this duration). Final diagnosis was migraines. Doctor prescribed Fioricet and gave me a long-acting steroid. Some pain is still there, but symptoms have mostly stopped. Waves of quick bursts of pain on localized areas on the left side of my head are still occuring.

On 09-Apr-2021, the patient received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) 1 dosage form. On 09-Apr-2021, the patient experienced SEIZURE (4 seizures) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and life threatening) and ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (anaphylaxis) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and life threatening). On 09-Apr-2021, SEIZURE (4 seizures) had resolved and ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (anaphylaxis) was resolving. 19 2021-04-19 weakness, numbness Patient had parked in the COVID vaccine waiting area, and was observed to fall forward onto his stee... Read more
Close
Patient had parked in the COVID vaccine waiting area, and was observed to fall forward onto his steering wheel within a few minutes of parking by 2 other participants waiting in the car next to him. One of them immediately notified one of the parking lot volunteers who came and got me within 1 minute of this observation. 2 students and I came quickly to the open drivers side door and began talking to assess the situation. Mr. Bannister appeared pale, mildly diaphoretic (sweating) and slightly confused as to the passage of time, but was able to state and spell his name and talk coherently about his circumstances. He stated that he was not allergic to anything that he knew about, and that he had no prior history of similar reactions to vaccines or medicines although he had not taken any shots in several years. He noted that he had not eaten anything since breakfast (now mid-afternoon). He described himself as initially feeling weak, faint, and nauseated with his vaccinated arm feeling heavy and numb. He also reported that he had a sensation of blurriness before passing out, but denied any spinning sensation, visual loss or ringing in the ears. There were no obviously visible abrasions or bleeding on his face or forehead. The nursing students brought a chair, and we elevated his legs and gave him some water to drink during the time we were monitoring his vital signs. He refused a cupcake because of the nausea, but as time progressed he gained facial color and was more comfortable in conversing. His hands had equal muscle grip and strength, visible fingernail beds were pink and his capillary refill was less than 3 seconds. Towards the end of our monitoring, he did accept some nuts and M & Ms to eat. A University Safety Medical Report was completed by the appropriate safety personnel. He was fully AAO x 3 at the end of our monitoring, and stated that if he felt better he would drive to his apartment (less than 5 minutes away) but would wait for his girlfriend to get out of class if he did not feel fully capable of driving. We encouraged him to eat something light when he got home, to use cool water/warm water soaks at his shot site, exercise his arm, and to take an NSAID for pain relief the next day. We recommended that he eat something light before his second shot (which had already been scheduled), that he bring someone with him the next time, and as a precaution to wait 30 minutes following the second shot. He left at 3: 15 pm driving his car without any apparent difficulties. An online report was completed for the incident 04/20/2021.

Dizziness/ dizzy; Weakness/ very weak; Seizures; Fainted; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of SEIZURE (Seizures), SYNCOPE (Fainted), DIZZINESS (Dizziness/ dizzy) and ASTHENIA (Weakness/ very weak) in a 19-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. No Medical History information was reported. On 07-May-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 07-May-2021, the patient experienced SEIZURE (Seizures) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant) and SYNCOPE (Fainted) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant). On 16-May-2021, the patient experienced DIZZINESS (Dizziness/ dizzy) (seriousness criterion hospitalization) and ASTHENIA (Weakness/ very weak) (seriousness criterion hospitalization). The patient was hospitalized on 07-May-2021 due to SEIZURE and SYNCOPE, then on 16-May-2021 due to ASTHENIA and DIZZINESS. The patient was treated with PARACETAMOL (TYLENOL) at an unspecified dose and frequency. At the time of the report, SEIZURE (Seizures) and SYNCOPE (Fainted) outcome was unknown and DIZZINESS (Dizziness/ dizzy) and ASTHENIA (Weakness/ very weak) had not resolved. The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown. No concomitant medications were reported. Description: During the day of the injection, at 5 to 10 minutes, the patient fainted and had seizures that required hospitalization. Also, on 16 May 2021 the patient required hospitalization again because of the dizziness and weakness. The patient was still dizzy and was very weak. The patient had a consult with a neurologist and who told that the symptoms were probably becasue of the vaccine. Other treatment information included unspecified pill for dizziness at the hospital. Myocarditis; Acute onset of chest pain; Soreness of the arm; A spontaneous report was received from a physician concerning a 20-year-old, male patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced soreness of the arm, acute onset of chest pain, and myocarditis. The patient's medical history, as provided by the reporter, included asthma, and allergy to egg, peanut and tree nuts. Concomitant medications reported included dupilumab, montelukast, budesonide / formoterol, cetirizine, albuterol and epinephrine. On 29 Dec 2020, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 025J20A) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 26 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of events, the patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 028L20A) intramuscularly in the left deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 26 Jan 2021, after receiving the second dose of the vaccine, the patient reported soreness of the arm for 3 to 4 days. On 30 Jan 2021, the patient presented to the hospital with acute onset of left sided chest pain. The physician reported that the patient developed myocarditis. Consent for Safety to follow up was received. Treatment for the events, as reported, included patient's concomitant medications of dupilumab, montelukast, budesonide / formoterol, cetirizine and albuterol. No additional treatment information was provided. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The event, soreness of the arm, was resolved on unknown date. The event acute onset of chest pain and myocarditis was not resolved at the time of this report.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 20 year old male with medical history of multiple allergies, who was hospitalized with serious unexpected events of chest pain and myocarditis and a non-serious unexpected event of pain in extremity. The chest pain and myocarditis occurred 33 days after first dose and 4 days after last dose of mRNA-1273. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of mRNA-1273 and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

20 2021-03-25 involuntary muscle movements, inability to speak, unresponsive to stimuli Approximately 10 minutes after receiving the Moderna vaccine, this writer was called to the patient ... Read more
Close
Approximately 10 minutes after receiving the Moderna vaccine, this writer was called to the patient room by other staff. The patient was extremely confused and not speaking to anyone. He was gazing to the left and not making eye contact with this writer, who was loudly talking to the patient. Multiple attempts were made to get the patient's attention with no success. The patient then began to involuntarily raise his bent left arm in front of his face and then back down to his side. In this writer's opinion, the patient was having a silent seizure. This writer sat with the patient, who became aware approximately 15 seconds later. He was able to answer questions and was quickly reoriented. At this point this writer had the staff call 911 for further evaluation. After answering basic questions appropriately., this writer gathered vital signs on the patient . The first set of vitals were: bp 88/48, pulse 60, respirations 14/min, oxygen saturation 93% on room air, temp 98.5. After small conversation with the patient, another set of vitals were taken: bp 94/70, pulse 68, respirations 15/min, oxygen saturation 95% on room air, temp 98.8. We then had the patient drink some water, then had him lie down in the patient room until EMS arrived. By the time they arrived, the patient was completed reoriented and laughing with office staff. EMS evaluated the patient and deemed him safe to go home with his friend driving. This writer walked the patient to the car to assess balance and coordination. This writer informed the patient and his friend to call 911 if symptoms returned. The patient agreed.

Close
My left arm was sore starting a few minutes after the vaccine. This soreness last through that night. When I woke up the next day, my arm was extremely sore and I was very dizzy. Additionally, my pulse felt fast but my heartbeat seemed to have less strength. My breathing felt more shallow like I wasn't getting as much oxygen from the air that I breathed in as I should. For the first two weeks, the dizziness was very strong. Now, at the three-week mark, it is more manageable and life is somewhat returning to normal. I visited an ENT doctor and their diagnosis was that my dizziness was not being caused by a preexisting medical condition. Their prediction was that I would be fine, though looking back, I downplayed the severity of my vertigo. At its worst, I felt that, when I went for a walk outside, the surface was the Earth was violently spinning through space, with me stuck to the surface. It felt paralyzing. My body felt almost stuck in shock. I was afraid I would be stuck with this dizziness for the rest of my life since it was so long-lasting. Now, I am taking ginger pills and am watching my sodium intake. I feel better but am extra vigilant about taking ginger and not stressing myself too much. I do not plan on getting a second shot since some of my symptoms mirror those of anaphylaxis.

The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. Concurrent medical conditions included ADD. On 30-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 27-Apr-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 27-Apr-2021, the patient experienced SLUGGISHNESS ("extreme sluggishness), EYE SWELLING ("swollen eyes, they were basically swollen shut), OCULAR HYPERAEMIA (dark and red coloration around his eyes/his eyes were red), DYSPNOEA (difficulty breathing), PAIN IN EXTREMITY (sore arm), FATIGUE (fatigue) and PYREXIA (he had a high fever just by touching him, he was extremely warm to the touch.). On 28-Apr-2021, the patient experienced GENERALISED TONIC-CLONIC SEIZURE (Grand mal seizure) (seriousness criteria hospitalization, medically significant and intervention required). The patient was hospitalized from 28-Apr-2021 to 28-Apr-2021 due to GENERALISED TONIC-CLONIC SEIZURE. On 28-Apr-2021, GENERALISED TONIC-CLONIC SEIZURE (Grand mal seizure) had resolved. At the time of the report, SLUGGISHNESS ("extreme sluggishness), EYE SWELLING ("swollen eyes, they were basically swollen shut), OCULAR HYPERAEMIA (dark and red coloration around his eyes/his eyes were red), DYSPNOEA (difficulty breathing), PAIN IN EXTREMITY (sore arm), FATIGUE (fatigue) and PYREXIA (he had a high fever just by touching him, he was extremely warm to the touch.) had not resolved. On an unknown date, Chest X-ray: (Inconclusive) No results were provided. On an unknown date, Computerised tomogram: (Inconclusive) No results were provided. On an unknown date, Urine analysis normal: (Inconclusive) No results were provided. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. No concomitant medication were reported. Treatment included Advil for fever, Maxipime, Keppra for seizure prevention and normal saline. 21 2021-07-06 tremor Day of vaccination, patient experienced uncontrollable tremors in both arms. In response, patient to... Read more
Close
Day of vaccination, patient experienced uncontrollable tremors in both arms. In response, patient took a dose of ibuprofen, performed stretches and took a nap; symptoms subsided. On June 28th, 2021, patient experienced another bout of tremors in both extremities at around 10am, which persisted for approximately 12 hours. After a televisit with CRNP, patient was referred to Emergency room. Patent reported to Hospital with continuing tremors. Doctors examined the patient's blood, as they head suspected rhabdomyolysis after ruling out any neurological causes for the symptoms. All bloodwork came back negative. Doctors intravenously injected 1.5 liters of saline fluid, after which the tremors subsided. Patient was thus discharged from ER. On July 2, 2021, at around 6pm, patient experienced sporadic tremors in right arm, which subsided after approximately 30 minutes. On July 4th, 2021, patient experienced frequent and sporadic tremors in both arms during the course of the day. Symptoms only subsided with sleep. On July 5th, 2021, patient experienced tremors in all four extremities during the course of the day. Consumed electrolyte water, remembering that the saline IV fluids had previously treated the tremors. Frequency and intensity of tremors decreased after patient consumed 48 fl oz of electrolyte water. Tremors fully subsided in sleep. On July 7th, 2021, patient was admitted to Family Practice and referred for a CT scan while still experiencing tremors. Scan showed no hemorrhages or growths in brain. Patient continues to experience sporadic and frequent tremors in all four extremities, varying in length and intensity.

This provider was speaking to the pt and performed a sternal rub to elicit a response, pt remained unresponsive and with eyes closed. Pt remained in this state for approximately 10 seconds. Pt noted to suddenly have some muscular rigidity to arms and torso and in order to prevent injury upon possible onset of seizure activity, pt was lowered to the floor by this provider and RN . Once on the ground the pt was relaxed and opened his eyes. Pt was immediately verbally responsive and asked if he passed out. Pt was able to sit up and was assisted into the wheelchair. Pt moved to treatment area where vitals and blood glucose were obtained. (@1525 BG- 104 mg/dL, VS BP 116/72, HR bradycardic @51 bpm, O2 sat 95%). Patient responses/speech was clear and pt was oriented to self, place, time and situation. Pt stated that he felt nauseated upon sitting in the observation area and admitted that he only had a coffee today, nothing to eat all day and attributed this as the cause of his reaction. Pt verbalized that he would not respond to the hospital with the paramedics and was encouraged to at least call someone to take him to the hospital. This provider spoke with the patient?s mother and explained the events. The patient?s mother stated that the patient had febrile seizures when approximately 4 years old, associated with asthma exacerbations; but pt was evaluated with a neurologist and there were no abnormal findings. Pt admitted that he has a similar syncopal episode after washing a laceration and seeing his finger bleeding. Pt states this was a few years ago and witnessed by his father that told the patient he initially fainted and then became momentarily rigid before responding appropriately (similar to today?s events). Ambulance - arrival @1536 report given and pt stated he was feeling better and declined further evaluation in truck and also declined transport to ED ( departed at 1545). Pt?s overall condition, appearance, including color was much improved. Pt denied any allergies or medication history. Past medical hx of febrile seizures at approximately age three and four, childhood asthma and one syncopal episode as an adult. Pt girlfriend arrival and she agreed to drive patient from the vaccine clinic. Pt and girlfriend were both provided with an explanation of the many concerning causes of syncope and the necessity for further evaluation in the Emergency department to rule out any underlying conditions. Both patient and girlfriend verbalized understanding and although they still declined to respond to ED directly from the clinic, both did agree to respond to ED if any changes in mental status occurred. Pt lives alone, but agreed to stay with parents and family in order to have others watch him for any changes. Pt was advised to followup with PCP and made aware that an provider would contact him tomorrow to check on his status, understanding verbalized and agreed with plan of care. Pt in no acute distress, awake, alert and oriented. Color within normal limits for and departed facility with girlfriend at 15:56, steady gait noted. Patient?s appointment for second dose was cancelled and will need to obtain clearance prior to second vaccine dose.

Less than 24 hours after the second dose of the Moderna vaccine, I developed tingling and sensitivity all over my body, fatigue, and tachycardia. I reported to the ED of UPMC Shadyside with a bmp of 130. My heart rate remained above 100 bmp throughout the course of the day. The ED team did not find signs of infection, blood clots, or heart inflammation after a multitude of lab tests. After a series of IV fluids and pain medications they were unable to lower my heart rate or find a cause and so I was discharged with instructions to hydrate and rest. The following day my heart rate remained elevated from my typical resting rate. It is not until today (6/27/2021), nearly 72 hours after the injection, that my heart rate has stabilized down to a more typical resting bpm for me.

24 2021-03-01 pain in extremity I did not feel anything shortly after the injection, but later in the evening, started to develop a ... Read more
Close
I did not feel anything shortly after the injection, but later in the evening, started to develop a normal post-vaccine soreness. I thought little of it and went to bed. I woke up just after 3am with chills, fever, and worsened arm pain, to the point that it restricted my arm's range of motion and speed of motion. Interestingly, the arm is not red or swollen, but is painful near the injection site, and the area around my clavicle on that side is somewhat swollen, but not red or painful (likely a lymph node). I was unable to get back to sleep due to these side effects (primarily chills and fever). After a few hours of trying to get back to sleep, I took some Tylenol and tried to eat breakfast. I was unable to keep much down, and had to arrange a day off of my internship, and was finally able to sleep on and off for the next few hours. The symptoms have somewhat lessened, but have not resolved, after about 22.5 hours post-injection. I fully expect this to resolve or mostly resolve by the 48 hour mark. I mostly found this unusual due to the severity of the reaction and after only the first dose, and wondered if my young age could have something to do with the clearly robust immune response so soon after inoculation.

I kept a log of the events that occurred. Notes: 25mg amitriptyline taken nightly for the last month, 200mg motrin I?ve never taken pain killers before this, time is in military. Mar 18 1430 (1 hour 30 mins after my shot) i have a compressing headache toward the back of my head so i take 1 motrin. 1700 i head home, take 1 amitriptyline and head straight to sleep. ( i have no apatite so no dinner ) Mar 19 0100 The pain starts, it?s unbearable. I am sweating heavily and im also shivering cold. i have a high fever I have body aches which turns my shivering into shaking which keeps my wife up all night. In my dreams i feel pain. I talked to my deceased mother, i hold my deceased cat and i relive some of my most regrettable moments. 0700 I wake up, the bed is soaking wet. I take a motrin and get dressed. it takes me an hour longer to get ready for work because, the pain has sapped my energy. My supervisor sends me home seeing how horrible I look. 0900 I take an amitriptyline and lay down. I ask me wife to close to the storm shutters to darken the room. They are normally pretty quiet to close but, this time they are deafeningly loud. I struggled to get 1 hour of sleep. 1500 I wake up due to shaking so bad that i hit my head on the wall. I then take 2 motrin and about 30 mins later i notice theres a tightness in my chest. i take 1 tums. I know that my body is exhausted from the pain and my mind is clouded but i really wanted to do all of the tasks that i was planning on doing this weekend. All of the tasks end up failing. 2100 i try the tasks again and end up failing again. 20 Mar 0100. I eat a pear and 2 cheetos. i do not take a amitriptyline and i lay down. i have no pain or fever. (Dream start) The dream i had is of me watching myself get thrown around by a ghost. The ghost possesses my body for a short time. I grab some kittens (cats are a comfort to me so im guessing that my subconscious trying to reel me back in) I then wake my sleeping wife and tell her theres a ghost and we need to leave. We walk outside and im in an old neighborhood that i grew up in, everything darkens and im in pitch black feeling my way around a room. I open my eyes and im in a hotel. The front desk staff will not let me take the kittens up to my room so i leave them. When i walk into the room, it?s full of kittens (dream end) and i wake up 21 Mar 0900 I wake up and I have a sore throat and tightness in my chest. The soreness prevents me from going back to sleep and the tightness in my chest causing some anxiety. Once I calm myself down and convince myself that im not having a heart attack I take 2 motrin and some tums and the pain goes away from the day. These could be some withdrawals from not taking amitriptyline since 19 mar in the morning. This is still happening as I write this report. (23 March 2021)

Earlier today, a Moderna patient at 3213 experienced a 15-30 second seizure after receiving his 1st Moderna vaccine. Shortly after sitting down for his 15-minute post immunization observation period, patient X began seizing resulting in him falling to the ground from a seated position to his left side and seizing for about 15-20 seconds. Patient was positioned in a left lateral recumbent position. Code white was called and EMT arrived on site within 10 minutes. Patient's immunization questionnaire did NOT have any contraindications that would warrant he should not receive the vaccine. Patient reported no allergies to medications/past immunizations/foods and reported no seizure and/or neurological condition. Once recovered and at baseline, patient reported having a light breakfast this morning and also having a needle phobia that may have played a role in his adverse response. Shortly after recovering, patient was coherent and aware of person, place, and time. He remained weak and fatigue and BP readings from EMT indicated hypotension. EKG was normal. Patient's mother happened to be waiting outside in the car. One of my associates was able to call her in and we updated here on the event. EMT recommended, and patient agreed, to be taken to the hospital for further examination.

Pericarditis. Initial symptoms were noticeable upon waking up the morning after receiving the vaccine, ~ 20 hours after vaccination. Initial symptoms: extremely elevated heart rate (~160 bpm). Heart rate fell to more reasonable, but still high, ~120 bpm after 2-3 hours. Roughly 36 hours after vaccination, began noticing soreness in the chest. Upon waking the following day (~48 hours after vaccination), chest soreness had progressed to pain (rating: 4/10), which remained roughly 6 hours to roughly 1400 that day, when the pain subsided along with all symptoms. Later, at roughly 2000 the same day (~58 hours after vaccination), there was a sudden and extreme flair up of chest pain (rating: 8/10) which radiated down the inside of both arms, this lasted 1.5 hours and then subsided just as suddenly as it came on. I went to sleep, then was woken up by another extreme episode of pain (rating: 7/10) at 0230 the morning of 15 May, again extreme chest pain radiating down both arms.

25 2021-05-23 weakness 24 hours after the second Moderna dose, I began to feel very weak with a strong headache and a low g... Read more
Close
24 hours after the second Moderna dose, I began to feel very weak with a strong headache and a low grade fever. By Thursday (48 hours after vaccination) the headache was very strong and by that night it was debilitating. The fever had increased as well to between 101-102 degrees. Thursday night Friday I treated symptoms with alternating doses of Ibuprofen and Acetaminophen, which succeeded in reducing the fever but did not rid of the headache. Saturday the debilitating headache persisted with extreme light sensitivity and nausea. The pain became so great Saturday night that my wife took me to the Emergency Room. There they performed a brain scan with an MRI that came back normal and treated the pain with Morphine. I was sent home around 8am Sunday morning with a prescription for Toradol. The pain did not decrease with the Toradol and by 6pm Sunday I was vomiting blood and the pain was excruciating. At the advice of my primary care doctor, I went back to the Emergency Room. In the Emergency department they performed a Lumbar Puncture and collected spinal fluid for testing, as well as blood for lab work. The pain was managed with Fentanyl. Late that evening the Hospital admitted me. I was given two more MRI's of the brain - one with contrast. I also underwent an upper scope of my esophagus, stomach, and upper colon which found 3 small ulcers likely due to the high volume of NSAID pain relievers taken over the previous days. The lumbar puncture revealed that my white blood cell count was 51 and they officially diagnosed aseptic meningitis.
